  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "92490486e2d15a38",
      "text": "In the words of George Bernard Shaw, “What we want to see is the child in pursuit of knowledge, not knowledge in pursuit of the child.” Unleashing curiosity and valuing it as a crucial ingredient in engaged, purposeful learning is the beginning and end of our work at Griffin. We believe that without curiosity there is no joyful or deeply engaged learning. Curiosity is our linchpin; it drives learning, both for our learners and for ourselves. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b29d447c13ff36fb",
      "text": "Curiosity is the element of hunger; we want our learners to be hungry to learn. Active over passive, joyful over dull. I could reference the experts, but I’ve seen it with my own eyes. We’ve seen the difference curiosity makes to the learning process and we know which we’d rather. Teaching with curiosity is more delightful for us as educators, too. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e876522a74a6a42a",
      "text": "A classroom where curiosity is the spark that ignites learning is a more joyful place to be. The act of learning is more joyful, the journey more joyful, the grapple propelled in active pursuit of the joy, the success more joyful. With an intrinsic desire to know, knowledge acquisition is transformed from work to learning. We work for others; we learn for ourselves. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "63b4c94c6e5e8f2b",
      "text": "Curiosity hasn’t always been viewed as a compliment, a desired attribute or a gift. It once had connotations of being odd or strange, eccentric and different; not traits one would want to have been associated with. In today’s times, curiosity is more highly regarded and its power is increasingly coming to the forefront."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6f571df5107dab0b",
      "text": "To explore further? State and Trait curiosity: trait is innate, state can be created by educators...\nIt is said that producing literate and numerate individuals should be the two main focuses of education with curiosity considered an innate trait passed down through our genetic code. It is also said that this inherited trait curiosity varies between individuals; how curious we are at birth and throughout our life. The question of whether one can learn to be more curious is then an interesting, complex idea. Being literate and numerate only seems insufficient in our ever-changing world. Without curiosity, innovation, a core 21st century practice, seems that it might be limited. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a75760c1377b29b5",
      "text": "If we are to educate learners to thrive in our complex world then the idea that curiosity actually helps them to learn, and heaven-forbid helps them to even find some joy along the way in the process, needs to be illuminated for them. At Griffin, our ongoing relationship with Wayne Craig is helping us to uncover the nature, theories, characteristics and types of curiosity. We are learning that the drive, incongruity and information gap theories can be deployed to ignite teaching and learning through specific actions; that understanding the characteristics of curiosity can shift our role in the classroom; that harnessing the types of curiosity can insight more authentic learner-centred exploration. "
    },
